NOTE: Cell lines not found in CRISPRGeneEffect or PRISM meta are excluded from analysis.
Minimum n=5 per group for CERES comparison (Mann-Whitney). If n<5, report descriptive
statistics only and note as underpowered.

## Processing protocol (pre-registered)

Step 1: Load CRISPRGeneEffect.csv, extract columns:
  SOS1 (6654), RAF1 (5894), PTPN11 (5781), KRAS (3845), BRAF (673)

Step 2: Load PRISM meta, get depmap_id → ccle_name mapping.
  LUAD: secondary_tissue == "lung_NSC"
  SKCM: primary_tissue == "skin" AND secondary_tissue == "melanoma"

Step 3: Map CCLE names to mutation status using pre-registered curated annotation above.
  Accept partial matches: "A549" matches "A549_LUNG" etc. (strip tissue suffix for lookup)
  If a cell line is in CRISPR but not in PRISM meta: include only if CCLE name is
  unambiguously identifiable in the pre-registered list.

Step 4: Compute group means and Mann-Whitney U test for each pairwise comparison.
  LUAD KRAS-MT vs KRAS-WT: for SOS1, RAF1, PTPN11, KRAS
  SKCM BRAF-V600E vs BRAF-WT: for SOS1, RAF1, PTPN11, KRAS, BRAF

Step 5: Compute Cohen's d for each comparison.
  Effect size convention: d < −0.2 = negligible; −0.5 = small; −0.8 = medium; −1.2 = large

Step 6: For H2, compute delta_CERES = mean(MT) − mean(WT) for SOS1, RAF1, SHP2.
  H2 tests whether |delta_SOS1| > |delta_RAF1| AND |delta_SOS1| > |delta_SHP2|.

## Hypotheses

### H1: SOS1 CERES score lower (more essential) in KRAS-MT vs KRAS-WT LUAD

Structural prediction: SOS1 is the top DAMPER in KRAS-MT LUAD (z_dr=+4.184) and
elevated DAMPER in EGFR-MT LUAD (z=+3.620), but near-zero in KRAS-WT/EGFR-WT LUAD
(z=−0.193). The structural elevation is specific to RAS-activated contexts.

CERES interpretation: If SOS1 is genuinely more functionally essential in KRAS-MT LUAD
(as the positive feedback GEF), its CERES score should be more negative in KRAS-MT
cell lines.

H1 CONFIRMED if:
  mean_CERES(SOS1, KRAS-MT) < mean_CERES(SOS1, KRAS-WT)
  AND Mann-Whitney p < 0.10 (one-tailed: KRAS-MT more essential)
  AND Cohen's d < −0.3 (at least small effect size)

H1 DENIED if:
  mean_CERES(SOS1, KRAS-MT) >= mean_CERES(SOS1, KRAS-WT)
  OR p >= 0.10

H1 PARTIAL if:
  Directional (KRAS-MT more essential) but p >= 0.10 OR |d| < 0.3

### H2: SOS1 differential exceeds RAF1 and SHP2 differentials (pathway-specificity control)

If SOS1's CERES shift in KRAS-MT is due to GEF-specific positive feedback (allosteric
RAS-GTP activation at second site), it should be larger than the shift for:
  - RAF1: direct KRAS effector, always co-activated with KRAS-MT (pathway load control)
  - SHP2/PTPN11: upstream RAS activator via RTK, less relevant in constitutive KRAS-MT

H2 CONFIRMED if:
  |delta_CERES(SOS1)| > |delta_CERES(RAF1)|
  AND |delta_CERES(SOS1)| > |delta_CERES(PTPN11)|
  where delta = mean(KRAS-MT) - mean(KRAS-WT)

H2 DENIED if:
  RAF1 differential >= SOS1 differential
  OR PTPN11 differential >= SOS1 differential

H2 PARTIAL if one control exceeds SOS1 but not both.

### H3: SOS1 NOT more essential in BRAF-V600E vs BRAF-WT SKCM (RAS-bypass test)

BRAF-V600E activates MEK directly, bypassing RAS. SOS1 (a RAS-GEF) should have no
special essentiality advantage in BRAF-V600E cells vs BRAF-WT cells.

If H3 is CONFIRMED (no SOS1 differential in SKCM), this establishes that the H1
finding is specific to KRAS activation, not a general MAPK-hyperactivation effect.

H3 CONFIRMED if:
  |mean_CERES(SOS1, BRAF-V600E) - mean_CERES(SOS1, BRAF-WT)| < 0.15 CERES units
  OR Mann-Whitney p > 0.30 (no evidence of differential essentiality)

H3 DENIED if:
  SOS1 is MORE essential in BRAF-V600E SKCM (mean CERES more negative, p < 0.10)
  This would suggest MAPK-load (not KRAS-specific) drives SOS1 essentiality.

### H4: KRAS CERES lower in KRAS-MT LUAD (positive control)

KRAS should be essential in KRAS-MT cell lines (KRAS addiction). This is the
well-established positive control for the dataset and annotation quality.

H4 CONFIRMED if:
  mean_CERES(KRAS, KRAS-MT) < mean_CERES(KRAS, KRAS-WT) AND p < 0.05

H4 DENIED if KRAS is NOT more essential in KRAS-MT. This would invalidate the
annotation/dataset and render H1–H3 uninterpretable.

## Pre-registration caveats

1. Mutation annotation is literature-curated, not from a programmatic mutation file.
   Cell lines with ambiguous KRAS status in published literature are excluded.
   A footnote will list all included/excluded lines and their documented mutation status.

2. CERES score convention: negative = essential. Lower score = more essential.
   All direction claims use this convention consistently.

3. Group sizes are expected to be small (n=10–20 per LUAD group, n=8–15 per SKCM group).
   Statistical power is limited; results will be reported with exact n, p, and d.
   If n < 5 per group, report descriptive only (no statistical test).

4. The PRISM meta file covers ~1120 cell lines; CRISPRGeneEffect may cover different
   lines. Intersection is used for lineage annotation. If a KRAS-MT line is in CRISPR
   but not PRISM, it is included using its CCLE name directly.

5. Multiple testing: 4 genes × 2 comparisons = 8 tests. No Bonferroni correction applied
   (each hypothesis is pre-registered and directional). Report uncorrected p-values.

6. Cross-experiment validation: After D22, add row to Driver=ANCHOR symmetry table:
   "SOS1 z_dr=+4.184 in KRAS-MT LUAD → SOS1 CERES differential in KRAS-MT LUAD".
   This closes the structural-to-functional validation loop for SOS1.

